  You have to be more than 10 levels higher to single pull mobs.  Say you are level 40 and there are two mobs next to each other.  If both mobs are level 29, you can nuke one mob and the other mob will not come along with it.  If both mobs are level 30 and you nuke one, both mobs will come along.  At least that's the rule at level 60.  I can single pull mobs up to level 49.  I don't know if it scales with level or not. <br>
<br>
  Elfnom<br>
  60 mage <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#989dca><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub102.ezboard.com/bthemagicianstower.showUserPublicProfile?gid=eloinapyromancer>Eloina Pyromancer</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Arch Mage</span><br>  Posts: 404<br> <font color=#333333>(2/9/03 3:02:58 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub102.ezboard.com/fthemagicianstowerthingstokill.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=443.topic&index=3>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title>   Re: There is a level limit</span><hr size=1> I think there's more to it than that, though.  LOS matters, as does the type of spell you cast, for example.  There are times when I can cast an annul and get one, whereas if I cast a nuke, I get both.  Or if two can see me I'll get both, whereas if only one can see me, I'll only get one.<br>
<br>
It's an art... something you learn zone by zone, mob by mob. <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#dcdeed><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub102.ezboard.com/bthemagicianstower.showUserPublicProfile?gid=skildpade>skildpade</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Elementalist</span><br>  Posts: 169<br> <font color=#333333>(2/11/03 2:42:17 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub102.ezboard.com/fthemagicianstowerthingstokill.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=443.topic&index=4>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title>   Re: There is a level limit</span><hr size=1> Level is a great factor in this, but not the only one. The amount of damage you do is a factor too, which is why the white ceramic band or malo**** is a favorite for pulling.<br>
<br>
Think of every mob (including yourself) as having two circles around them, one called aggro range and one called assist range.<br>
<br>
When you are young, the aggro circle is large and any mob that comes within this circle will attack you if it cons less than doubious.<br>
<br>
The assist circle is usually different in size and even if you are outside the aggro circle, if you attack one mob within another mobs assist range, you will get two or more mobs on you. This is why screwy pathing is so dangerous, because the mob you attacked may pass thru another mobs assist range.<br>
<br>
The relative diameters of the circles are based on the level difference between you and the mob and vary from one type of mob to another type mob. <br>
<br>
Line of sight also matters, but the games calculations of LoS has always been screwy. One example of this is that in many zones you can find a spot where you clearly can see a mob, but it is impossible to hit it even if it looks like it shouldn't be too far away.<br>
 <p>nmee - commander of mudhills<br>
